-- ICICI Bank Leads Biggest Advance in India's Sensex Index in Five Weeks
-- Rajhkumar K Shaaw
-- 2010-08-02T11:34:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-08-02/icici-bank-leads-biggest-advance-in-india-s-sensex-index-in-three-weeks.html

          
          
             India’s stocks rose the most in six
weeks, led by  ICICI Bank Ltd.  after Credit Suisse Group AG
upgraded its shares. Agriculture-related shares gained as the
nation’s weather bureau said rain in July exceeded forecasts.  
 ICICI Bank , the second-biggest lender, advanced 3.8 percent
after Credit Suisse raised the shares to “outperform” as
quarterly profit increased 17 percent. Gujarat State Fertilizers
& Chemicals Ltd. soared 9.2 percent, leading gains among peers.
Good monsoon rainfall will boost planting of sugar cane and rice,
Farm Minister  Sharad Pawar  said today.  Bajaj Auto Ltd.  climbed
after July two-wheeler sales rose to a record.  
 “There are no concerns on the economy side,” said  Aneesh Srivastava , the Mumbai-based chief investment officer at IDBI
Fortis Life Insurance Co., who manages $325 million in assets.
“There will be a strong rebound in the agriculture sector.”  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 212.92, or 1.2 percent, to 18,081.21, its steepest gain
since June 21. The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on the National Stock
Exchange rose 1.2 percent to 5,431.65. The  BSE 200 Index 
increased 1.2 percent to 2,307.50.  
 ICICI Bank advanced 3.8 percent to 939.55 rupees, its best
one-day gain since May 26.  Ashish Gupta  and  Deepak Ramineedi ,
analysts at Credit Suisse, rated the stock “outperform,”
raising it from “neutral,” and increased their estimate for
earnings-per-share growth this year to 6 percent and to 15
percent for the 12 months through March 2012, citing lower
credit costs.  
 Fertilizer Stocks  
 The lender’s first-quarter net income rose to 10.3 billion
rupees ($223 million), matching the average of 18 analyst
estimates compiled by Bloomberg.  
 Gujarat State Fertilizers jumped 9.2 percent to 312.3
rupees, its highest close since January 2008.  National
Fertilizers Ltd.  soared 2 percent to 116.95 rupees, while
Gujarat Narmada Valley Fertilizers Co. gained 1.4 percent, to
116.4 rupees.  
 Rainfall in July, the wettest month of the June-September
monsoon season, was 102.5 percent of the 50-year average of
292.4 millimeters, said D. Sivananda Pai, a director at the
India Meteorological Department. Agriculture accounts for about
a fifth of India’s economy.  
 Bajaj Auto  
 Bajaj Auto, the second-largest motorcycle maker, increased
1.4 percent to 2,725.5 rupees. Its sales of motorcycles and
three-wheelers climbed 65 percent to a record 318,415 units in
July.  TVS Motor Co. , the third-largest motorcycle maker,
advanced 1.3 percent to 140.85 rupees. The Chennai, south India-
based company’s two-wheeler sales jumped 35 percent last month,
while motorcycle sales gained 42 percent.  
 India’s manufacturing growth accelerated in July. The
Purchasing Managers’ Index rose to 57.6 from 57.3 in June, HSBC
Holdings Plc and Markit Economics said in an emailed statement
today. A reading above 50 indicates expansion.  
 “Growth remains strong,” said  Kishor Ostwal , managing
director of CNI Research (India) Ltd., a publicly traded
equities research provider in Mumbai. “It looks like monsoon
will be normal this year, which will boost our gross domestic
product growth.”  
 Sterlite Industries (India) Ltd. , the biggest copper and
zinc producer, advanced 2.9 percent to 179.85 rupees. Copper for
delivery in three months gained 1.1 percent on the London Metal
Exchange.  All of the six main metals traded on the LME advanced,
taking aluminum, zinc, nickel and lead to the highest intraday
prices since May.  
 Hindalco  
 Hindalco Industries Ltd., the biggest aluminum producer,
rose 2.5 percent to 164.4 rupees.  Tata Steel Ltd. , the biggest
producer of the alloy, jumped 1.9 percent to 547.25 rupees.  
 Overseas  funds  bought a net  44.4 billion rupees  of Indian
equities on July 29, the 18th straight day that purchases have
exceeded sales, raising total investments in the stocks this
year to 476.9 billion rupees, according to the nation’s market
regulator.  
 Inflows from overseas reached a record 834.2 billion rupees
in 2009, exceeding the high set two years ago in local currency
terms, as the biggest advance in 18 years lured foreign funds.
They sold a record 529.9 billion rupees of shares in 2008,
triggering a record annual decline.  
 The following were among the most active on the exchange:  
 Bank of India (BOI IN) surged 7 percent to 439.4 rupees,
its highest close since October 2009. The state-owned lender’s
first-quarter net income climbed 24 percent.  
 Cairn India Ltd  (CAIR IN) gained 2 percent to 340.95 rupees.
The operator of the nation’s biggest land-based oilfield was
raised to “buy” from “sell” by Goldman Sachs Group Inc.
analysts led by  Nilesh Banerjee . The analysts raised their
share-price estimate to 7.2 percent to 370 rupees.  
 Indiabulls Real Estate Ltd.  (IBREL IN) rose 2.1 percent to
167.2 rupees. Indiabulls Infratech Ltd. paid 4.74 billion rupees
for the Podar Mills (Process House) land in central Mumbai,
National Textile Corp., or NTC, said in a statement. The amount
was 90 percent more than the reserve price for the land.  
